The issue with the code is that the `findViewById` method is being called before the `Activity` has had a chance to create the views. This is because the `findViewById` method is being called in the constructor of the `MainActivity` class, which is being called before the `onCreate` method.

To fix this issue, you should move the `findViewById` call inside the `onCreate` method, like this:
```kotlin
public class MainActivity extends AppCompatActivity {
    TextView txtView1;
    Button Button01;
    Button Button02;
    Button Button03;
    Button Button04;
    Button Button05;
    Button Button06;
    Button Button07;
    Button Button08;

    @Override
    protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
        setContentView(R.layout.activity_main);

        txtView1 = (TextView) findViewById(R.id.textView1);
        Button Button01 = (Button) findViewById(R.id.Button01);
        Button Button02 = (Button) findViewById(R.id.Button02);
        Button Button03 = (Button) findViewById(R.id.Button03);
        Button Button04 = (Button) findViewById(R.id.Button04);
        Button Button05 = (Button) findViewById(R.id.Button05);
        Button Button06 = (Button) findViewById(R.id.Button06);
        Button Button07 = (Button) findViewById(R.id.Button07);
        Button Button08 = (Button) findViewById(R.id.Button08);

        // Rest of the code
    }
}
```
This way, the views are only created when the `onCreate` method is called, and the `findViewById` method can find the views in the layout.
